T1  - Introduction: ‘Race’, Learning and Teaching in Social Policy in Higher Education
AN  - 2610018151
AB  - [...]of growing concern amongst the discipline, the present authors were commissioned by the Social Policy Association (SPA) to undertake an audit of the teaching of ‘race’ within social policy courses (Craig et al., 2019).

The audit comprised various approaches: a review of the literature (which was found to be sparse), an analysis of published data and other UCAS statistics relating to student admissions, retention and progression; data on student and staff profiles, interviews with a series of ‘experts’ – that is, a group of academics with wide-ranging areas of expertise and, in some cases, many years of teaching social policy – and a survey of Higher Education Institutions (HEI) including social policy in their undergraduate and postgraduate taught course offers.

Overall, the conclusions of the report were dismal reading for the social policy community, made more dismal by the fact that, set against a rising tide of racism in the country at large, particularly since the 2016 Referendum (but certainly predating it), it should surely be a key role of social policy to confront the growth of racism within welfare provision and outside it; to challenge the messages being delivered at institutional and individual levels by the media, by the government and by right-wing political parties such as Brexit and UKIP, which place the blame for all the country’s ills at the feet of so-called ‘immigrants’ (bear in mind that more than 50 per cent of all UK ethnic minorities were born and grew up in this country); and to remind the wider population of the immense contribution that migrants are making and have made to the UK’s welfare provision despite all the obstacles put in their way.

The need for this, we would argue, is now even more critical than it has been in recent years as the government has embarked on what can only be characterised as a cohesive and determined pushback against those, apparently politically motivated activists and academics, who believe that the UK remains a profoundly racist society in its institutions, structures and policies, This argument has been fought out in the last two years over a variety of terrains, including the Grenfell fire, the toppling of statues and other icons ‘celebrating’ the contribution of slave owners to British (imperial) history, the growth of the Black Lives Matters movement (which might finally put the issue of ‘race’ firmly in the public eye), the distorted and partial account of racism delivered by the widely-challenged Sewell Commission report, and the latest iteration of government policy on immigration and asylum which notes that the system is failing but blames that failure on those fleeing violence and war rather than the structure, policies and misperformance of the Home Office and indeed of the Home Secretary, accused of being racist and forgetful of her own family’s history as, effectively, a victim of the ethnic cleansing of Idi Amin.
