AN  - 2431122709
AB  - The summit diplomacy between Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump in March 2018 brought forth the issue of China’s marginalization in Northeast Asian affairs. While China’s perceived loss of influence in North Korea since Kim Jong-un took power went viral in traditional and social media, the most audacious believed that the young leader was “defecting” to the West with his nuclear weapons. The article asks if the claims can be substantiated by the Sino-DPRK relations in 2012–2017 and if the claims failed to see the comprehensive nature of an asymmetrical relationship. China’s top interest in North Korea is regime stability, code-named “peace and stability of the Korean Peninsula,” that has strong geostrategic implications connected with the ever rising rivalry between China and the USA. This top interest coincides with North Korea’s security paranoia as it is exemplified in its nuclear and missile programs. Using these two premises, the article explores how China’s policy behaviors toward Pyongyang in 2012–2017 correspond with these two premises and how the key issues in China-DPRK relations reflect these two premises. The article argues that the China-DPRK relations did not fracture in the first 6 years of Kim Jong-un’s rule. The bilateral ties have experienced a spirited rejuvenation after the Kim-Trump summit diplomacy because China remains motivated to nurture the relations in new circumstances for their respective national interests.
